{
  "local_port": 49634,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best web prototyping/mockup tool?",
  "response": "The \"best\" web prototyping or mockup tool depends on your specific needs, team collaboration, budget, and the level of detail you require. Here are some of the most popular and highly regarded tools in 2023:\n\n### **1. Figma**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Figma is a cloud-based design tool that allows real-time collaboration, making it ideal for teams. It\u2019s versatile, offering both prototyping and design features, and has a robust plugin ecosystem.\n- **Best for:** Teams, collaborative environments, and UX/UI designers.\n- **Pricing:** Free for small teams; paid plans for additional features and storage.\n\n### **2. Adobe XD**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Adobe XD is a powerful tool with a clean interface, ideal for creating wireframes, prototypes, and UI designs. It integrates seamlessly with other Adobe Creative Cloud apps.\n- **Best for:** Designers already in the Adobe ecosystem.\n- **Pricing:** Free starter plan; paid plans for advanced features.\n\n### **3. Sketch**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Sketch is a vector-based design tool that\u2019s widely used for creating interfaces and prototypes. It has a large plugin library and a strong community.\n- **Best for:** Mac users and UI/UX designers.\n- **Pricing:** Subscription-based; one-time purchase also available.\n\n### **4. InVision Studio**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** InVision is known for its prototyping features, allowing interactive and animated prototypes. It\u2019s great for user testing and feedback.\n- **Best for:** UX designers focusing on interactive prototypes.\n- **Pricing:** Free for individual use; paid plans for teams.\n\n### **5. Axure RP**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Axure is a robust tool for creating highly detailed, interactive prototypes. It\u2019s ideal for complex projects and documentation.\n- **Best for:** Advanced users and complex projects.\n- **Pricing:** Paid; offers perpetual licenses and subscriptions.\n\n### **6. Proto.io**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Proto.io specializes in interactive and animated prototypes, making it a great choice for high-fidelity designs.\n- **Best for:** Designers needing advanced interactions and animations.\n- **Pricing:** Paid; offers a free trial.\n\n### **7. Marvel**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Marvel is a user-friendly tool for creating wireframes, prototypes, and user testing. It integrates with tools like Sketch and Figma.\n- **Best for:** Beginners and small teams.\n- **Pricing:** Free for limited projects; paid plans for more features.\n\n### **8. Balsamiq**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Balsamiq is a low-fidelity wireframing tool with a sketch-like interface. It\u2019s great for quick, conceptual designs.\n- **Best for:** Rapid wireframing and brainstorming.\n- **Pricing:** Paid; offers desktop and cloud versions.\n\n### **9. Framer**\n- **Why it\u2019\u2019s great:** Framer is a powerful tool for creating interactive and responsive prototypes. It also supports code-based design for advanced users.\n- **Best for:** Designers with coding skills or those needing high interactivity.\n- **Pricing:** Free for personal use; paid plans for teams.\n\n### **10. Webflow**\n- **Why it\u2019s great:** Webflow combines design and development, allowing you to create responsive websites and prototypes that can be exported as code.\n- **Best for:** Designers who want a no-code website builder.\n- **Pricing:** Free tier available; paid plans for hosting and advanced features.\n\n### **How to Choose the Right Tool:**\n- **For collaboration:** Figma or InVision.\n- For **high-fidelity prototypes:** Proto.io, Framer, or Axure RP.\n- For **low-fidelity wireframes:** Balsamiq.\n- For **Adobe users:** Adobe XD.\n- For **Mac users:** Sketch or Figma.\n- For **advanced interactions:** Framer or Axure RP.\n\nAlways consider your workflow, team size, and project complexity when choosing a tool. Many of these tools offer free trials, so you can test them before committing.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
